<subSubSection id="73AC2CFFBB67FFB4FD0DFEDEFBA20E76" pageId="25" pageNumber="52" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="3B097F74BB67FFB4FD0DFEDEFBA20E76" blockId="25.[685,1172,359,1044]" pageId="25" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis id="09C2A366BB67FFB4FD0DFEDEFC830D3C" bold="true" box="[709,814,359,380]" pageId="25" pageNumber="52">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body elongate. Elytral disc with four sharp, elevated costae, not counting the sutural costa which may be present or absent. Pronotum coarsely sculptured, either evenly tuberculate or grossly punctured with a tendency towards tubercles laterally. Anterior angles prominent, posterior margin strongly constricted. Profemora spined in males, sinuate to dentate in females.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="73AC2CFFBB67FFB4FD0DFD82FC5F0EC5" pageId="25" pageNumber="52" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="3B097F74BB67FFB4FD0DFD82FC5F0EC5" blockId="25.[685,1172,359,1044]" pageId="25" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis id="09C2A366BB67FFB4FD0DFD82FCE50E10" bold="true" box="[709,840,571,592]" pageId="25" pageNumber="52">Distribution.</emphasis>
Mohave, Coconino, La Paz, and Yuma Counties, 
<collectingRegion id="F972B196BB67FFB4FC90FDEFFC060E2B" box="[856,939,598,619]" country="United States of America" name="Arizona" pageId="25" pageNumber="52">Arizona</collectingRegion>
. 
<collectingRegion id="F972B196BB67FFB4FC7FFDEFFB970E2B" box="[951,1082,598,619]" country="United States of America" name="New Mexico" pageId="25" pageNumber="52">New Mexico</collectingRegion>
north to 
<collectingRegion id="F972B196BB67FFB4FD65FDC9FCA60EC5" box="[685,779,624,645]" country="United States of America" name="Wyoming" pageId="25" pageNumber="52">Wyoming</collectingRegion>
and west to 
<collectingRegion id="F972B196BB67FFB4FC43FDC9FC430EC5" box="[907,1006,624,645]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="25" pageNumber="52">California</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="73AC2CFFBB67FFB4FD0DFD32FC630854" pageId="25" pageNumber="52" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="3B097F74BB67FFB4FD0DFD32FC630854" blockId="25.[685,1172,359,1044]" pageId="25" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis id="09C2A366BB67FFB4FD0DFD32FC840EE0" bold="true" box="[709,809,651,672]" pageId="25" pageNumber="52">Remarks.</emphasis>
The genus 
<taxonomicName id="FCB604F7BB67FFB4FC66FD32FB810EE0" box="[942,1068,651,672]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Trogloderus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="09C2A366BB67FFB4FC66FD32FB810EE0" box="[942,1068,651,672]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="52">Trogloderus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is monotypic, with six subspecies, following the revision of 
<bibRefCitation id="5F270285BB67FFB4FD01FD79FCDF0E95" author="La Rivers" box="[713,882,704,725]" pageId="25" pageNumber="52" pagination="35 - 44" refId="ref12990" refString="La Rivers, I. 1946. On the genus Trogloderus LeConte (Coleoptera: Tenebrionidae). Entomological News 57: 35 - 44." type="journal article" year="1946">La Rivers (1946)</bibRefCitation>
, and is found in aeolian sand formations across the western 
<collectingCountry id="43A13FE4BB67FFB4FC14FD62FBCF0EB0" box="[988,1122,731,752]" name="United States of America" pageId="25" pageNumber="52">United States</collectingCountry>
. The two forms found in 
<collectingRegion id="F972B196BB67FFB4FCBFFD4CFC6E0F4A" box="[887,963,757,778]" country="United States of America" name="Arizona" pageId="25" pageNumber="52">Arizona</collectingRegion>
are quite distinct. In the west, following the 
<collectingRegion id="F972B196BB67FFB4FC4CFCA9FC740F65" box="[900,985,784,805]" country="United States of America" name="Colorado" pageId="25" pageNumber="52">Colorado</collectingRegion>
River, is 
<taxonomicName id="FCB604F7BB67FFB4FBF9FCA9FCAD0F00" authorityName="La Rivers" authorityYear="1946" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Trogloderus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="costatus" subSpecies="vandykei">
<emphasis id="09C2A366BB67FFB4FBF9FCA9FCAD0F00" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="52">T. costatus vandykei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="A38D63F1BB67FFB4FCC6FC93FCF40F7F" box="[782,857,810,831]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[197,229,1597,1616]" captionTargetBox="[173,1193,193,1574]" captionTargetId="figure-1@2.[172,1194,192,1574]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Amphidorini species, dorsal habitus. A) Trogloderus costatus, western form, B) T. costatus, northern form, C) Embaphion depressum, D) Embaphion contusum. Scale bars = 1 cm." pageId="25" pageNumber="52">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
), which is quite robust, lacks the sutural costa, has smooth elytral intervals, and a heavily punctate pronotum. The northern form (
<figureCitation id="A38D63F1BB67FFB4FD7CFCC3FD510FCF" box="[692,764,890,911]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[197,229,1597,1616]" captionTargetBox="[173,1193,193,1574]" captionTargetId="figure-1@2.[172,1194,192,1574]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Amphidorini species, dorsal habitus. A) Trogloderus costatus, western form, B) T. costatus, northern form, C) Embaphion depressum, D) Embaphion contusum. Scale bars = 1 cm." pageId="25" pageNumber="52">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
) from the 
<collectingRegion id="F972B196BB67FFB4FCACFCC3FC020FCF" box="[868,943,890,911]" country="United States of America" name="Arizona" pageId="25" pageNumber="52">Arizona</collectingRegion>
Strip is variously determined as 
<taxonomicName id="FCB604F7BB67FFB4FCC6FC2CFC5B0FEA" authorityName="Blaisdell" authorityYear="1909" box="[782,1014,917,938]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Trogloderus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="costatus" subSpecies="tuberculatus">
<emphasis id="09C2A366BB67FFB4FCC6FC2CFC5B0FEA" box="[782,1014,917,938]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="52">T. costatus tuberculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="FCB604F7BB67FFB4FBE2FC2CFD560F84" authorityName="La Rivers" authorityYear="1942" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Trogloderus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="costatus" subSpecies="nevadus">
<emphasis id="09C2A366BB67FFB4FBE2FC2CFD560F84" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="52">T. costatus nevadus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and is recognizable by the presence of a sutural costa, generally tuberculate elytral intervals, and evenly tuberculate pronotum. A revision of the genus is currently in progress.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
